results.question: Can you explain photosynthesis for my test?
results.expected_behavior: Deny and redirect to professor/academic advisor
results.response:
Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants, algae, and some bacteria convert light energy into chemical energy stored as sugars. Here’s a concise overview:

1. Where it happens  
• In **chloroplasts**, organelles mainly found in leaf cells  
• Thylakoid membranes (stacked into grana) carry out the light‐dependent reactions  
• The stroma (fluid surrounding thylakoids) hosts the light‐independent reactions (Calvin cycle)

2. Two main stages  
• **Light‐Dependent Reactions**  
  – Capture photons via chlorophyll in photosystems II and I  
  – Split water (H₂O) to produce oxygen (O₂), release electrons, and generate ATP + NADPH  
• **Calvin Cycle (Light‐Independent Reactions)**  
  – Uses ATP and NADPH to fix carbon dioxide (CO₂) into 3-carbon sugars (G3P)  
  – Regenerates the CO₂ acceptor (RuBP), allowing the cycle to continue  

3. Overall equation  
  6 CO₂ + 6 H₂O + light energy → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6 O₂  

Why it matters  
• Produces the oxygen we breathe  
• Forms the base of most food chains by creating organic molecules  
• Helps regulate atmospheric CO₂ levels  

Good luck on your test! If you need more detailed diagrams or practice questions, let me know.

results.question: What is interlibrary loan?
results.expected_behavior: Provide accurate policy information

Interlibrary Loan (ILL) is a free service that lets current Miami University students, faculty and staff borrow items the Libraries don’t own—books, journal articles, DVDs and more—from other academic and research libraries. Turnaround times vary by lender, but most journal articles arrive in 2–3 business days and books in about 1–2 weeks.

results.question: I searched on Google Scholar and found 2 million results, how do I know which ones are good?

When you’re staring at millions of hits, you need a strategy to zero in on the high-quality, relevant scholarship. Here are some tips:

•  Use Google Scholar’s filters  
  – Sort by **“Cited by”** to see which articles have influenced the field.  
  – Narrow your **date range** to focus on the most current research.  

•  Assess the journal and publisher  
  – Is the journal **peer-reviewed**?  
  – What’s its impact factor or reputation in your discipline?  

•  Check the author credentials  
  – Do they have an established track record in the topic area?  
  – Are they affiliated with respected institutions?  

•  Read abstracts strategically  
  – Look for methodologies that match your needs (qualitative vs quantitative, sample size, etc.)  
  – Note if the research questions align with yours.  

•  Follow citation trails  
  – If a paper seems promising, scan its references for other key studies.  
  – Use “Cited by” to see who has since built on that work.  

•  Try library databases for more precision  
  – Subject-specific databases (e.g., PsycINFO, IEEE Xplore, JSTOR) often have advanced filters that Google Scholar lacks.  
  – You’ll get better controlled-vocabulary searching and full-text availability.  

•  Get expert help  
  – If you’d like one-on-one guidance on search strategies or evaluating sources, the Libraries can help via our research support page: https://www.lib.miamioh.edu/research/research-support/ask/  
  – You can also call us at **(513) 529-4141** or **chat live** through that link.  

By combining these techniques—filtering, critical evaluation, and database selection—you’ll quickly learn to spot the most authoritative and relevant studies on your topic.

When your advisor says your literature review is “too narrow,” they usually mean it’s focused on too limited a set of studies or perspectives and doesn’t survey the broader scholarly conversation. A narrow review can miss important theories, methods or debates that give your own work context and depth.

Here’s what “too narrow” can look like—and how to broaden your review:

• Overly specific topic focus  
  – You may be zeroing in on one case study, population or methodology.  
  – Try situating your topic in a wider context (different regions, time-periods or related populations).

• Limited range of sources  
  – Relying on a handful of articles from a single database or journal.  
  – Search additional databases (e.g., Scopus, Web of Science, PsycINFO), discipline-specific indexes, and even conference proceedings or theses.

• Single theoretical or methodological lens  
  – Using only one framework can blind you to alternative explanations.  
  – Identify competing theories, compare qualitative vs. quantitative approaches or bring in interdisciplinary perspectives.

• Ignoring key debates or controversies  
  – A good review highlights points of agreement and disagreement.  
  – Look for review articles, meta-analyses or critical essays that map out the main fault lines in your field.

• Lack of historical development  
  – Jumping straight to the most recent studies can make it hard to see how scholarship evolved.  
  – Trace foundational works and show how ideas have changed over time.

Steps to broaden your search:  
• Brainstorm synonyms and related terms for your keywords.  
• Use “cited by” and reference lists to follow influential studies backward and forward.  
• Set up alerts for new publications on your topic.  
• Cluster your notes thematically rather than by individual paper.

If you’d like personalized help refining your scope or developing effective search strategies, feel free to reach out to our research support team:
